<https://n2t.net/ark:/27023/4b83614b1cb0855caad0e4ff882b44ef> <https://colonialcollections.nl/schema#description> "Schildering in waterverf en inkt op papier. Religieuze volksschildering, voorstellend twee vrouwelijke onsterfelijken, seonin, met een hond. Lan Caihe (Kor.: Kam Ch'ae-ha) wordt onder meer beschouwd als de beschermster van de bloemenhandel. Soms is deze figuur een manspersoon die luid roept alsof hij dronken is. Deze figuur wordt half-gek beschouwd en wordt geacht veel en makkelijk te kunnen reizen. Ook zijn attribuut is de bamboe bloemenmand. Hij is de beschermer van de tuiniers.\r\nHe Xiangu (Kor.: Ha Sŏn-go) zou in de zevende eeuw geleefd hebben. Van deze figuur wordt verhaald dat zij op haar veertiende of vijftiende jaar in een hemels wezen veranderde door het innemen van een medicijn van parelmoer. Op een dag, op weg naar het hof keizerin Wu (690-705) die haar opgeroepen had, verdween ze van de aardbodem. Ze maakte lange tochten om jonge bamboescheuten voor haar zieke moeder te verzamelen. Volgens andere overleveringen was zij een taoïstische non tijdens de Song-dynastie. Door ambtenaren en geleerden wordt zij aangeroepen om de toekomst en het lot te voorspellen. Zij is te herkennen aan de peul of een lotusbloem in haar ene hand.\r\nOp de achterkant van het papier staat in een hoek met inkt het Chinese karakter voor '10'.\r\n\r\nWhen Korea entered the Chosŏn Dynasty, its ambassadors were sent to China to learn Daoist Fasts and Offerings rituals. Cheng Emperor of the Ming Dynasty sent persons specially assigned for taking 600 kinds of Daoist moral tracts to Korea. Because a Daoist organization was not formed in Korea, it vanished into folk beliefs or other religious beliefs (Heavenly Daoism). \r\n\r\nDaoist (Taoist) immortals are considered 'patron saints' of the Daoist belief. Their images were representative of typical individuals and represented wealth and poverty, old age, and youth, male and female. It was believed that ordinary human beings could learn the sectets of nature and become immortal, through hard study. These immortals were idolised and respected for their wisdom, humour, and moral lessons. Normally, only eight immortals are officially recognised, but legends describe several more. As the Eight Daoist Immortals to which they belong, these emblems are representations of longevity. \r\n\r\nTwo women immortals are depicted in this painting. \r\nLan Cai-he (Kam Ch'ae-ha in Korean pronunciation) is generally regarded as a woman who continuously chants a doggerel denouncing the fleeting nature of life and its delusive pleasures. Her emblem is the flower-basket and she is considered the patron saint of florists. \r\nHere Lan Cai-he is depicted as a woman, but in some cases, she is also described as a man who sings loudly as if intoxicated. He was considered 'semi-crazed by many' It was said that he traveled far and wide with great ease. His trademark was a bamboo basket as he was considered the 'patron saint' of gardeners. \r\nHe Xian-gu (Ha Sun-ko in Korean pronunciation) purportedly lived in the 7th century. When she was fourteen to fifteen years old, she became a celestial being as as result of taking the Daoist medicine of mother-of-pearl powder. She disappeared one day when on her way to the court of the Empress Wu (AD 690-705) who had sent for her. She was revered for the long distances she travelled to pick dainty bamboo shoots for her mother who was very ill. Some say that she was a Daoist Nun during the Sung dynasty. Literates and officials often make inquiries of her on their future and destiny. She carries a lotus flower or seed pod as her trademark." .
